# Fluff Date: 2026-02-28 17:47:08
overview:<p>The Phantom is a 40-ton Clan OmniMech introduced in 3052 by Clan Wolf, pushed into production by Khan Phelan Ward shortly before the Refusal War with Clan Jade Falcon. Designed around Ward's extensive experience with Inner Sphere tactics, the Phantom was intended to push the concept of a medium-sized reconnaissance OmniMech to its most extreme limits. Sharing many technical details with the Ice Ferret, the Phantom trades that design's weaponry and armor for raw speed and an emphasis on electronic warfare capability.</p><p>After the Wars of Reaving, the Phantom replaced the Fire Moth among the remaining Home Clans due to its similar reconnaissance role and heavier profile. The introduction of the Wulfen by Clan Wolf eventually relegated the Phantom to secondary status, but renewed demand led Clan Wolf to sell the design specifications to Clan Sea Fox, who retooled a Bloodhound production line to manufacture the OmniMech and now offers it to any interested party.</p>

capabilities:<p>The Phantom is built on a lightweight Type-A endo steel chassis and propelled by a Light Force 360-rated extra-light fusion engine, achieving a blistering top speed of 151 kph that places it among the fastest medium OmniMechs in any Clan touman. This extraordinary speed serves as the design's primary defensive asset, as six tons of Composite A-2 ferro-fibrous armor provides only modest protection for a 40-ton platform. The chassis mounts no jump jets, relying entirely on ground speed for tactical mobility.</p><p>With only 6.5 tons of available pod space, the Phantom is severely limited in the firepower it can bring to bear, a deliberate trade-off that reinforces its reconnaissance mission profile. The Primary configuration exemplifies this philosophy, packing an ECM suite, active probe, and TAG laser designator into the chassis to create a highly capable electronic warfare and artillery spotting platform. An LRM-5 launcher, ER medium laser, and ER small laser provide enough firepower to engage targets of opportunity without encouraging pilots to seek prolonged engagements.</p><p>The Phantom's principal weakness lies in the tension between its limited pod space and the expectations placed upon it. While its speed and improved sensor suite make it an exceptional scout, any configuration that emphasizes direct combat capability must sacrifice the electronics package that defines the design's core identity. Modern configurations have attempted to address this by incorporating advanced weapons that maximize damage per ton of pod space.</p>

deployment:<p>Alternate Configuration C pushes the Phantom's close-combat capability to its maximum by mounting eight ER small lasers and an ER medium laser, all linked to an advanced targeting computer for increased accuracy. A rear-firing flamer provides anti-infantry capability and area denial. The sheer volume of precision laser fire this configuration can deliver at close range has earned it a fearsome reputation; Inner Sphere warriors have compared engaging a Phantom C to suffering innumerable small wounds that cumulatively prove fatal. The targeting computer ensures that nearly every shot finds its mark, making this configuration exceptionally efficient despite the individually modest damage output of each weapon.</p>

history:<p>The Phantom emerged from a period of intense internal conflict within Clan Wolf. Khan Phelan Ward, a former Inner Sphere mercenary who had risen through the Clan's warrior caste, recognized the value of dedicated reconnaissance and electronic warfare platforms that Inner Sphere militaries had long employed. The design was rushed into production at W-5 Facilities on Eden just before the Refusal War erupted in 3057, and the subsequent Crusader-Warden split left both factions desperate for equipment. With the Wolf Clan fractured, production of the Phantom continued to serve both the Wolves in Exile on Arc-Royal and the remnant Crusader Wolves.</p><p>The Wolves in Exile proved the Phantom's worth during Operation Bulldog and the subsequent incursion into Lyran Alliance space by Clan Jade Falcon. The design's speed and electronics suite proved invaluable for coordinating combined-arms operations alongside Inner Sphere forces, vindicating Ward's original design philosophy. Clan warriors from the Ice Hellions, Cloud Cobras, Snow Ravens, and Goliath Scorpions secured Phantoms from Clans Hell's Horses and Jade Falcon, who had in turn captured equipment from the Wolves. The Goliath Scorpions were so impressed with the design that they reverse-engineered it and began manufacturing Phantoms themselves.</p><p>The Wars of Reaving dramatically expanded the Phantom's role among the Home Clans. With the Fire Moth's production disrupted and many lighter OmniMechs lost in the fighting, the surviving Clans adopted the Phantom as a replacement for their fast reconnaissance assets. This second life proved temporary among the Spheroid Wolves, however, as the introduction of the Wulfen OmniMech created demand that outstripped Kallon Weapon Industries' capacity. Recognizing the Phantom's diminished priority, Clan Wolf sought assistance in retooling a Bloodhound factory on Keystone for renewed production. In exchange for this help, the ilKhanate received the Phantom's design specifications, and Clan Sea Fox now manufactures the OmniMech aboard the CSF Tsunami mobile production facility, offering it to all interested parties.</p><p>Within the Wolf Empire, the Phantom has become a probationary assignment, given to warriors before they earn the right to pilot the more prestigious Wulfen. Some MechWarriors have attempted to mimic Wulfen configurations using the Phantom's limited pod space, leading to several unofficial field configurations. The design's appearance on Solaris VII in 3145 and its continued use during Operation Kingbreaker demonstrate that the Phantom remains a viable reconnaissance platform, its speed and sensor capabilities ensuring relevance even as newer designs compete for production priority.</p>

